1 Combinatorial Analytic Relationship Score (CARS)- Testing all combos of BARS variables

To identify the optimal model, we will test all possible combinations of the variables chosen during feature selection; we will judge a model using a combination of features, called \(T\), via the Occam’s Score:

\[\text{Occam's Score}(T)=\text{RMSE}_{\text{test}}\Big(1+\gamma(n-1)\Big)\]

Models will be rewarded based upon having a lower RMSE and less total number of variables. The penalty for more variables is given as a percentage increase in RMSE because this ensures a uniform scale that each model can be judged off of. \(\gamma\) is a parameter controling how stiff the penalty is for adding one more variable. You can think of it as a tax rate: the higher the tax on a particular economic action, the less incentivized that action is - assuming a rational actor. Notice to that there is no penalty for \(n=1\) variables: this is because models with only one variables are the simplest possible models.

1.1 Generate all possible combination of variables

One important thing to note about this step is that the number of possible combinations grows exponentially as the number of selected features increase. Say we have \(m=8\) total features that we selected, then there are \(2^m-1\), or 127, possible combinations. So, the point here is that this step should only be done once you’ve successfully reduced your feature set.

1.1.1 Calculate the RMSEs of the Model for each Combination of features \(T\)

Here, all we’re doing is using basic decision trees - with no hyperparameterization - to get an idea how good of a model can be constructed from \(T\).

Code 
testTrainSplit = .8
numSetsofVars =length(varFam)
scores = []
varNums = []

for varSet ∈ varFam
    n = length(varSet)
    push!(varNums,n)
    dftest = select(barsdf,targetVar,varSet)
    y,X=unpack(dftest,==(targetVar),rng=123)
    if n<2
        X = DataFrame(varSet[1] => X)
    end

    tree = MLJDecisionTreeInterface.DecisionTreeRegressor()
    mach=machine(tree,X,y,scitype_check_level=0)
    
    MLJ.fit!(mach, rows=train)
    
    ŷtrain = MLJ.predict(mach,X[train,:])
    ŷtest = MLJ.predict(mach,X[test,:])
    
    RMSE = calcRMSE(y[test],ŷtest)
    score = RMSE
    push!(scores,score)
end

1.1.2 Score Plot

Once the the RMSEs for each \(T\) are known, then we just need to plot the score. Note that the scores are separated by bins. Most of the bins have labels like \(n=3\), \(n=4\) etc: \(n\) represents the number of features present in a particular \(T\). This gives us further insight into how the score behaves as we increase the number of variables present in the test sets. The optimal model is identified; afterward, we will use the same type of model - a hyperparamterized random forest model - to see if we have identified a more leaner and more accurate model!

Code 
m=length(varFam[numSetsofVars])
augscores =[]
γ=0.1
for i ∈ 1:length(varFam)
    num=length(varFam[i])
    push!(augscores, scores[i]*(1+γ*(num-1)))
end

augscores

scoreIdx=11
scoreplot = scatter(1:length(augscores),
                    augscores, 
                    label = "model scores",
                    markercolor = :black,
                    markershape = :+,
                    legend = :outertopright, 
                    ylims=(0,1.1*findmax(augscores)[1])
                    )
scatter!([findmin(augscores)[2]],[findmin(augscores)[1]], label = "best model: "*"#"*string(findmin(augscores)[2]))
ylabel!("Occam's Score")
xlabel!("Model Number")
title!("Score"*L"=RMSE(1+\gamma(n-1))"*" ("*L"\gamma="*string(round(γ,sigdigits=3))*")")
dividers = []
#m = length(varFam[numSetsofVars])
for n∈1:m
    idx = findfirst(item -> item == n, varNums)
    push!(dividers,idx)
end

for n∈1:m
    idx = findfirst(item -> item == n, varNums)
    vline!([dividers[n]-.5],primary = false)
    if n<m && m>2
        if abs(dividers[n+1]-dividers[n])>.25*abs(dividers[convert(Int,ceil(m/2))]-dividers[convert(Int,ceil(m/2))-1])
            annotate!([(dividers[n]+dividers[n+1])/2],[1.05*findmax(augscores)[1]],text("n="*string(n), :blue, :center, 6))
        end
    end
end

#if n<m && abs(dividers[n+1]-dividers[n])>.25*abs(dividers[convert(Int,ceil(m/2))]-dividers[convert(Int,ceil(m/2))-1])

initVertPos = .8*findmax(augscores)[1]
horzPos = 1.3*length(augscores)
i=.075*initVertPos
annotate!([horzPos],[initVertPos],text("Model Variables: ",:black,:center,8))
for string∈string.(varFam[findmin(augscores)[2]])
    annotate!([horzPos],[initVertPos-i],text(string,:red,:center,8))
    i+=.075*initVertPos
end

if save
    savefig(scoreplot,"Plots"*fileprefix*CaseStudy*"/ScorePlot"*ext)
end

2.3 Permutation Importance

The features are almost equivalently important: there are not massive dropoffs in relative importance which means there are nor more redundant or harmful features contained within our model.

Code 
bestPiPlot
